"Rodriguez-Garcia G., Molinos-Senante M., Hospido A., Hernández-Sancho F., Moreira M.T., Feijoo G.","Environmental and economic profile of six typologies of wastewater treatment plants",2011,"Water Research","45","18",,"5997","6010",,,10.1016/j.watres.2011.08.053,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80054049232&partnerID=40&md5=ff60459781b6df1dbc0ebf2acbd387b9","Department of Chemical Engineering, School of Engineering, University of Santiago de Compostela, 15782 Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Department of Applied Economics II, Faculty of Economics, University of Valencia, Campus dels Tarongers, 46022 Valencia, Spain","Rodriguez-Garcia, G., Department of Chemical Engineering, School of Engineering, University of Santiago de Compostela, 15782 Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Molinos-Senante, M., Department of Applied Economics II, Faculty of Economics, University of Valencia, Campus dels Tarongers, 46022 Valencia, Spain; Hospido, A., Department of Chemical Engineering, School of Engineering, University of Santiago de Compostela, 15782 Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Hernández-Sancho, F., Department of Applied Economics II, Faculty of Economics, University of Valencia, Campus dels Tarongers, 46022 Valencia, Spain; Moreira, M.T., Department of Chemical Engineering, School of Engineering, University of Santiago de Compostela, 15782 Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Feijoo, G., Department of Chemical Engineering, School of Engineering, University of Santiago de Compostela, 15782 Santiago de Compostela, Spain","The objective of wastewater treatment plants (WWTPs) is to prevent pollution. However, it is necessary to assess their sustainability in order to ensure that pollution is being removed, not displaced. In this research, the performance of 24 WWTPs has been evaluated using a streamlined Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) with Eutrophication Potential (EP) and Global Warming Potential (GWP) as environmental indicators, and operational costs as economic indicators. WWTPs were further classified in six typologies by their quality requirements according to their final discharge point or water reuse. Moreover, two different functional units (FU), one based on volume (m 3) and the other on eutrophication reduction (kg PO 4 3- removed) were used to further determine sustainability. A correlation between legal requirements and technologies used to achieve them was found: Organic matter removal plants were found to be less costly both in environmental and economic terms if volume was used as the functional unit, while more demanding typologies such as reuse plants showed a trade-off between lower EP and higher cost and GWP; however, this is overcome if the second FU is used instead, proving the sustainability of these options and that this FU better reflects the objectives of a WWTP. © 2011 Elsevier Ltd.","Eutrophication; Functional unit; Global warming; Life cycle thinking; Wastewater treatment costs","Economic indicators; Economic profiles; Environmental indicators; Functional unit; Functional units; Global warming potential; Legal requirements; Life cycle thinking; Life-cycle assessments; Operational costs; Organic matter removal; Quality requirements; Wastewater treatment costs; Wastewater treatment plants; Water reuse; Environmental regulations; Eutrophication; Global warming; Life cycle; Pollution; Rating; Sewage pumping plants; Sustainable development; Wastewater; Wastewater reclamation; Water conservation; Water supply; Water treatment plants; Wastewater treatment; organic matter; cost-benefit analysis; environmental economics; environmental legislation; eutrophication; global warming; life cycle analysis; organic matter; pollutant removal; research work; sustainability; technology transfer; trade-off; typology; wastewater; water treatment; water use; article; biotypology; cost; eutrophication; greenhouse effect; legal aspect; life cycle assessment; nonhuman; priority journal; quality control; waste water management; waste wa